  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Iccus of Tarentum was a Greek athlete and philosopher from the 5th century BCE. A native of the southern Italian city of Tarentum, he was an Olympic victor in the pentathlon. He is primarily remembered for his legendary self-discipline. Ancient sources report that he practiced extreme asceticism during training, abstaining from sex and following a strict diet to conserve his strength.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">This lifestyle of temperance led later writers to associate him with Pythagorean philosophy, which emphasized bodily and ethical discipline. The philosopher Plato mentions Iccus as a model of self-control. No writings by Iccus survive today. According to a later Byzantine source, he wrote a work on athletic training, but it is lost. He is known only through references by other authors.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Iccus is a significant figure for understanding the connection between Greek athletics and philosophy. He represents the ideal of the &quot;athlete-philosopher&quot; who applied intellectual principles to physical training. His reputation made him a lasting symbol of moderation and self-mastery. Later medical writers also cited him as an early example of using diet and a disciplined regimen to optimize athletic performance.</p>\n</div>",
  "affiliation_label": "Pythagorean",
